Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Peru. The Peruvian authorities have introduced measures to limit the spread of the virus.
On 15 March, Peru announced a national State of Emergency.
Borders and travel restrictions
All borders are closed for an initial period of 15 days with effect from 16 March.
Peru announced a ban on all flights arriving from and departing to Europe and Asia, with effect from Monday 16 March. The ban is for 30 days and could be extended.
If you’re in Peru, you’re advised to secure accommodation for this period. IPERU, the Peruvian Tourism Information Agency, is offering details of suitable accommodation.
If you wish to leave Peru, see Return to the UK
Local measures
Freedom of movement is restricted for the same period. The main exceptions are to purchase food or medication, or to visit banks. British nationals in Peru should follow the advice of the Peruvian authorities and abide by the measures in place. There will be police and armed forces patrols to impose the restrictions.
The Peruvian authorities have confirmed that drinking in public areas is prohibited during the State of Emergency. On 18 March, the President declared further measures to be enforced during the State of Emergency period. These include a mandatory curfew between the hours of 8pm and 5am each day (with exceptions for emergencies) and the complete ban of private vehicles from 5am on 19 March.
Private and public school classes in Peru have been suspended until 30 March.
Visas
During this period the Peruvian authorities have also confirmed that fees will be waived for overstays on visas owing to the State of Emergency.
Further information
More information (in Spanish) is available on the Ministry of Health (Ministerio de Salud) website or or by calling the 24/7 call free number 113, sending a WhatsApp message to +51 95284263 or emailing infosalud@minsa.gob.pe.
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
